Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Remove guards around b/143684500.

Several kernels have previously been disabled for std::complex due
to lack of operator support on device.  This is no longer the case,
and these kernels can now be enabled.

NOTE: we also needed to replace `a+=b` and `a-=b` with `a=a+b` and
`a=a-b` for use with `std::complex<T>` on device.  Unfortunately MSVC
does not stricly follow the c++ standard, and unnecessarily specializes
these operators. This prevents us from using Eigen's device-compatible
overrides.  Without these overrides, the original compound assignments
`+=` and `-=` silently fail on GPU.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JonathanSimon123/moby/commits/80cc1f1d6fb1d03014f7ef5d3a1e216538ddb855"},{"sha":"11ef8d3ba983d6fb0b1597e715bf45e3b882a507","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"overlay2: support "userxattr" option (kernel 5.11)

The "userxattr" option is needed for mounting overlayfs inside a user namespace with kernel >= 5.11.

The "userxattr" option is NOT needed for the initial user namespace (aka "the host").

Also, Ubuntu (since circa 2015) and Debian (since 10) with kernel < 5.11 can mount the overlayfs in a user namespace without the "userxattr" option.

The corresponding kernel commit: 2d2f2d7322ff43e0fe92bf8cccdc0b09449bf2e1
> **ovl: user xattr**
>
> Optionally allow using "user.overlay." namespace instead of "trusted.overlay."
> ...
> Disable redirect_dir and metacopy options, because these would allow privilege escalation through direct manipulation of the
> "user.overlay.redirect" or "user.overlay.metacopy" xattrs.

Fix issue 42055

Related to containerd/containerd PR 5076

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JonathanSimon123/moby/commits/4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb"},{"sha":"e31086320ea0305e2cc70490160ee30480471680","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove cli test for duplicate --net/--network opts

This seems to be testing a strange case, specifically that one can set
the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Indeed this used to work with older CLIs but newer ones error out when
validating the request before sending it to the daemon.

Opening this for discussion because:

1. This doesn't seem to be testing anything at all related to the rest
   of the test
2. Not really providing any value here.
3. Is testing that a technically invalid option is successful (whether
   the option should be valid as it relates to the CLI accepting it is
   debatable).
4. Such a case seems fringe and even a bug in whatever is calling the
   CLI with such options.

Remove cli test for duplicate --net/--network opts","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JonathanSimon123/moby/commits/e0c87f90cd93fbbfe1ba0e0abc80ba757e3b0a82"},{"sha":"5a664dc87d79ddc9f09c7a963c52f491999dc939","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"jsonfile: more defensive reader implementation

Tonis mentioned that we can run into issues if there is more error
handling added here. This adds a custom reader implementation which is
like io.MultiReader except it does not cache EOF's.
What got us into trouble in the first place is `io.MultiReader` will
always return EOF once it has received an EOF, however the error
handling that we are going for is to recover from an EOF because the
underlying file is a file which can have more data added to it after
EOF.

Tonis mentioned that we can run into issues if there is more error
handling added here. This adds a custom reader implementation which is
like io.MultiReader except it does not cache EOF's.
What got us into trouble in the first place is `io.MultiReader` will
always return EOF once it has received an EOF, however the error
handling that we are going for is to recover from an EOF because the
underlying file is a file which can have more data added to it after
EOF.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Remove guards around b/143684500.

Several kernels have previously been disabled for std::complex due
to lack of operator support on device.  This is no longer the case,
and these kernels can now be enabled.

NOTE: we also needed to replace `a+=b` and `a-=b` with `a=a+b` and
`a=a-b` for use with `std::complex<T>` on device.  Unfortunately MSVC
does not stricly follow the c++ standard, and unnecessarily specializes
these operators. This prevents us from using Eigen's device-compatible
overrides.  Without these overrides, the original compound assignments
`+=` and `-=` silently fail on GPU.

The "userxattr" option is needed for mounting overlayfs inside a user namespace with kernel >= 5.11.

The "userxattr" option is NOT needed for the initial user namespace (aka "the host").

Also, Ubuntu (since circa 2015) and Debian (since 10) with kernel < 5.11 can mount the overlayfs in a user namespace without the "userxattr" option.

The corresponding kernel commit: 2d2f2d7322ff43e0fe92bf8cccdc0b09449bf2e1
> **ovl: user xattr**
>
> Optionally allow using "user.overlay." namespace instead of "trusted.overlay."
> ...
> Disable redirect_dir and metacopy options, because these would allow privilege escalation through direct manipulation of the
> "user.overlay.redirect" or "user.overlay.metacopy" xattrs.

Fix issue 42055

Related to containerd/containerd PR 5076

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tfl0pz/moby/commits/4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb"},{"sha":"e31086320ea0305e2cc70490160ee30480471680","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove cli test for duplicate --net/--network opts

This seems to be testing a strange case, specifically that one can set
the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Indeed this used to work with older CLIs but newer ones error out when
validating the request before sending it to the daemon.

Opening this for discussion because:

1. This doesn't seem to be testing anything at all related to the rest
   of the test
2. Not really providing any value here.
3. Is testing that a technically invalid option is successful (whether
   the option should be valid as it relates to the CLI accepting it is
   debatable).
4. Such a case seems fringe and even a bug in whatever is calling the
   CLI with such options.

Remove cli test for duplicate --net/--network opts","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tfl0pz/moby/commits/e0c87f90cd93fbbfe1ba0e0abc80ba757e3b0a82"},{"sha":"5a664dc87d79ddc9f09c7a963c52f491999dc939","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"jsonfile: more defensive reader implementation

Tonis mentioned that we can run into issues if there is more error
handling added here. This adds a custom reader implementation which is
like io.MultiReader except it does not cache EOF's.
What got us into trouble in the first place is `io.MultiReader` will
always return EOF once it has received an EOF, however the error
handling that we are going for is to recover from an EOF because the
underlying file is a file which can have more data added to it after
EOF.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Skarlso/moby/commits/80cc1f1d6fb1d03014f7ef5d3a1e216538ddb855"},{"sha":"11ef8d3ba983d6fb0b1597e715bf45e3b882a507","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"overlay2: support "userxattr" option (kernel 5.11)

The "userxattr" option is needed for mounting overlayfs inside a user namespace with kernel >= 5.11.

The "userxattr" option is NOT needed for the initial user namespace (aka "the host").

Also, Ubuntu (since circa 2015) and Debian (since 10) with kernel < 5.11 can mount the overlayfs in a user namespace without the "userxattr" option.

The corresponding kernel commit: 2d2f2d7322ff43e0fe92bf8cccdc0b09449bf2e1
> **ovl: user xattr**
>
> Optionally allow using "user.overlay." namespace instead of "trusted.overlay."
> ...
> Disable redirect_dir and metacopy options, because these would allow privilege escalation through direct manipulation of the
> "user.overlay.redirect" or "user.overlay.metacopy" xattrs.

Fix issue 42055

Related to containerd/containerd PR 5076

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Skarlso/moby/commits/4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb"},{"sha":"e31086320ea0305e2cc70490160ee30480471680","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove cli test for duplicate --net/--network opts

This seems to be testing a strange case, specifically that one can set
the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Indeed this used to work with older CLIs but newer ones error out when
validating the request before sending it to the daemon.

Opening this for discussion because:

1. This doesn't seem to be testing anything at all related to the rest
   of the test
2. Not really providing any value here.
3. Is testing that a technically invalid option is successful (whether
   the option should be valid as it relates to the CLI accepting it is
   debatable).
4. Such a case seems fringe and even a bug in whatever is calling the
   CLI with such options.

Remove cli test for duplicate --net/--network opts","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Skarlso/moby/commits/e0c87f90cd93fbbfe1ba0e0abc80ba757e3b0a82"},{"sha":"5a664dc87d79ddc9f09c7a963c52f491999dc939","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"jsonfile: more defensive reader implementation

Tonis mentioned that we can run into issues if there is more error
handling added here. This adds a custom reader implementation which is
like io.MultiReader except it does not cache EOF's.
What got us into trouble in the first place is `io.MultiReader` will
always return EOF once it has received an EOF, however the error
handling that we are going for is to recover from an EOF because the
underlying file is a file which can have more data added to it after
EOF.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Remove guards around b/143684500.

Several kernels have previously been disabled for std::complex due
to lack of operator support on device.  This is no longer the case,
and these kernels can now be enabled.

NOTE: we also needed to replace `a+=b` and `a-=b` with `a=a+b` and
`a=a-b` for use with `std::complex<T>` on device.  Unfortunately MSVC
does not stricly follow the c++ standard, and unnecessarily specializes
these operators. This prevents us from using Eigen's device-compatible
overrides.  Without these overrides, the original compound assignments
`+=` and `-=` silently fail on GPU.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bai/moby/commits/80cc1f1d6fb1d03014f7ef5d3a1e216538ddb855"},{"sha":"11ef8d3ba983d6fb0b1597e715bf45e3b882a507","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"overlay2: support "userxattr" option (kernel 5.11)

The "userxattr" option is needed for mounting overlayfs inside a user namespace with kernel >= 5.11.

The "userxattr" option is NOT needed for the initial user namespace (aka "the host").

Also, Ubuntu (since circa 2015) and Debian (since 10) with kernel < 5.11 can mount the overlayfs in a user namespace without the "userxattr" option.

The corresponding kernel commit: 2d2f2d7322ff43e0fe92bf8cccdc0b09449bf2e1
> **ovl: user xattr**
>
> Optionally allow using "user.overlay." namespace instead of "trusted.overlay."
> ...
> Disable redirect_dir and metacopy options, because these would allow privilege escalation through direct manipulation of the
> "user.overlay.redirect" or "user.overlay.metacopy" xattrs.

Fix issue 42055

Related to containerd/containerd PR 5076

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bai/moby/commits/4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb"},{"sha":"e31086320ea0305e2cc70490160ee30480471680","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove cli test for duplicate --net/--network opts

This seems to be testing a strange case, specifically that one can set
the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Indeed this used to work with older CLIs but newer ones error out when
validating the request before sending it to the daemon.

Opening this for discussion because:

1. This doesn't seem to be testing anything at all related to the rest
   of the test
2. Not really providing any value here.
3. Is testing that a technically invalid option is successful (whether
   the option should be valid as it relates to the CLI accepting it is
   debatable).
4. Such a case seems fringe and even a bug in whatever is calling the
   CLI with such options.

Remove cli test for duplicate --net/--network opts","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bai/moby/commits/e0c87f90cd93fbbfe1ba0e0abc80ba757e3b0a82"},{"sha":"5a664dc87d79ddc9f09c7a963c52f491999dc939","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"jsonfile: more defensive reader implementation

Tonis mentioned that we can run into issues if there is more error
handling added here. This adds a custom reader implementation which is
like io.MultiReader except it does not cache EOF's.
What got us into trouble in the first place is `io.MultiReader` will
always return EOF once it has received an EOF, however the error
handling that we are going for is to recover from an EOF because the
underlying file is a file which can have more data added to it after
EOF.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/next-stack/moby/commits/80cc1f1d6fb1d03014f7ef5d3a1e216538ddb855"},{"sha":"11ef8d3ba983d6fb0b1597e715bf45e3b882a507","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"overlay2: support "userxattr" option (kernel 5.11)

The "userxattr" option is needed for mounting overlayfs inside a user namespace with kernel >= 5.11.

The "userxattr" option is NOT needed for the initial user namespace (aka "the host").

Also, Ubuntu (since circa 2015) and Debian (since 10) with kernel < 5.11 can mount the overlayfs in a user namespace without the "userxattr" option.

The corresponding kernel commit: 2d2f2d7322ff43e0fe92bf8cccdc0b09449bf2e1
> **ovl: user xattr**
>
> Optionally allow using "user.overlay." namespace instead of "trusted.overlay."
> ...
> Disable redirect_dir and metacopy options, because these would allow privilege escalation through direct manipulation of the
> "user.overlay.redirect" or "user.overlay.metacopy" xattrs.

Fix issue 42055

Related to containerd/containerd PR 5076

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/next-stack/moby/commits/4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb"},{"sha":"e31086320ea0305e2cc70490160ee30480471680","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove cli test for duplicate --net/--network opts

This seems to be testing a strange case, specifically that one can set
the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Indeed this used to work with older CLIs but newer ones error out when

Tonis mentioned that we can run into issues if there is more error
handling added here. This adds a custom reader implementation which is
like io.MultiReader except it does not cache EOF's.
What got us into trouble in the first place is `io.MultiReader` will
always return EOF once it has received an EOF, however the error
handling that we are going for is to recover from an EOF because the
underlying file is a file which can have more data added to it after
EOF.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Remove guards around b/143684500.

Several kernels have previously been disabled for std::complex due
to lack of operator support on device.  This is no longer the case,
and these kernels can now be enabled.

NOTE: we also needed to replace `a+=b` and `a-=b` with `a=a+b` and
`a=a-b` for use with `std::complex<T>` on device.  Unfortunately MSVC
does not stricly follow the c++ standard, and unnecessarily specializes
these operators. This prevents us from using Eigen's device-compatible
overrides.  Without these overrides, the original compound assignments
`+=` and `-=` silently fail on GPU.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Remove guards around b/143684500.

Several kernels have previously been disabled for std::complex due
to lack of operator support on device.  This is no longer the case,
and these kernels can now be enabled.

NOTE: we also needed to replace `a+=b` and `a-=b` with `a=a+b` and
`a=a-b` for use with `std::complex<T>` on device.  Unfortunately MSVC
does not stricly follow the c++ standard, and unnecessarily specializes
these operators. This prevents us from using Eigen's device-compatible
overrides.  Without these overrides, the original compound assignments
`+=` and `-=` silently fail on GPU.

Several kernels have previously been disabled for std::complex due
to lack of operator support on device.  This is no longer the case,
and these kernels can now be enabled.

NOTE: we also needed to replace `a+=b` and `a-=b` with `a=a+b` and
`a=a-b` for use with `std::complex<T>` on device.  Unfortunately MSVC
does not stricly follow the c++ standard, and unnecessarily specializes
these operators. This prevents us from using Eigen's device-compatible
overrides.  Without these overrides, the original compound assignments
`+=` and `-=` silently fail on GPU.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Remove guards around b/143684500.

Several kernels have previously been disabled for std::complex due
to lack of operator support on device.  This is no longer the case,
and these kernels can now be enabled.

NOTE: we also needed to replace `a+=b` and `a-=b` with `a=a+b` and
`a=a-b` for use with `std::complex<T>` on device.  Unfortunately MSVC
does not stricly follow the c++ standard, and unnecessarily specializes
these operators. This prevents us from using Eigen's device-compatible
overrides.  Without these overrides, the original compound assignments
`+=` and `-=` silently fail on GPU.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Remove guards around b/143684500.

Several kernels have previously been disabled for std::complex due
to lack of operator support on device.  This is no longer the case,
and these kernels can now be enabled.

NOTE: we also needed to replace `a+=b` and `a-=b` with `a=a+b` and
`a=a-b` for use with `std::complex<T>` on device.  Unfortunately MSVC
does not stricly follow the c++ standard, and unnecessarily specializes
these operators. This prevents us from using Eigen's device-compatible
overrides.  Without these overrides, the original compound assignments
`+=` and `-=` silently fail on GPU.

[{"sha":"4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix handling for json-file io.UnexpectedEOF

When the multireader hits EOF, we will always get EOF from it, so we
cannot store the multrireader fro later error handling, only for the
decoder.

Thanks @tobiasstadler for pointing this error out.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dgkh1975/moby/commits/4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb"},{"sha":"5a664dc87d79ddc9f09c7a963c52f491999dc939","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"jsonfile: more defensive reader implementation

Tonis mentioned that we can run into issues if there is more error
handling added here. This adds a custom reader implementation which is
like io.MultiReader except it does not cache EOF's.
What got us into trouble in the first place is `io.MultiReader` will
always return EOF once it has received an EOF, however the error
handling that we are going for is to recover from an EOF because the
underlying file is a file which can have more data added to it after
EOF.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Remove guards around b/143684500.

Several kernels have previously been disabled for std::complex due
to lack of operator support on device.  This is no longer the case,
and these kernels can now be enabled.

NOTE: we also needed to replace `a+=b` and `a-=b` with `a=a+b` and
`a=a-b` for use with `std::complex<T>` on device.  Unfortunately MSVC
does not stricly follow the c++ standard, and unnecessarily specializes
these operators. This prevents us from using Eigen's device-compatible
overrides.  Without these overrides, the original compound assignments
`+=` and `-=` silently fail on GPU.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/loot-king/moby/commits/80cc1f1d6fb1d03014f7ef5d3a1e216538ddb855"},{"sha":"11ef8d3ba983d6fb0b1597e715bf45e3b882a507","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"overlay2: support "userxattr" option (kernel 5.11)

The "userxattr" option is needed for mounting overlayfs inside a user namespace with kernel >= 5.11.

The "userxattr" option is NOT needed for the initial user namespace (aka "the host").

Also, Ubuntu (since circa 2015) and Debian (since 10) with kernel < 5.11 can mount the overlayfs in a user namespace without the "userxattr" option.

The corresponding kernel commit: 2d2f2d7322ff43e0fe92bf8cccdc0b09449bf2e1
> **ovl: user xattr**
>
> Optionally allow using "user.overlay." namespace instead of "trusted.overlay."
> ...
> Disable redirect_dir and metacopy options, because these would allow privilege escalation through direct manipulation of the
> "user.overlay.redirect" or "user.overlay.metacopy" xattrs.

Fix issue 42055

Related to containerd/containerd PR 5076

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/loot-king/moby/commits/4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb"},{"sha":"e31086320ea0305e2cc70490160ee30480471680","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove cli test for duplicate --net/--network opts

This seems to be testing a strange case, specifically that one can set
the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Indeed this used to work with older CLIs but newer ones error out when
validating the request before sending it to the daemon.

Opening this for discussion because:

1. This doesn't seem to be testing anything at all related to the rest
   of the test
2. Not really providing any value here.
3. Is testing that a technically invalid option is successful (whether
   the option should be valid as it relates to the CLI accepting it is
   debatable).
4. Such a case seems fringe and even a bug in whatever is calling the
   CLI with such options.

Tonis mentioned that we can run into issues if there is more error
handling added here. This adds a custom reader implementation which is
like io.MultiReader except it does not cache EOF's.
What got us into trouble in the first place is `io.MultiReader` will
always return EOF once it has received an EOF, however the error
handling that we are going for is to recover from an EOF because the
underlying file is a file which can have more data added to it after
EOF.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Remove guards around b/143684500.

Several kernels have previously been disabled for std::complex due
to lack of operator support on device.  This is no longer the case,
and these kernels can now be enabled.

NOTE: we also needed to replace `a+=b` and `a-=b` with `a=a+b` and
`a=a-b` for use with `std::complex<T>` on device.  Unfortunately MSVC
does not stricly follow the c++ standard, and unnecessarily specializes
these operators. This prevents us from using Eigen's device-compatible
overrides.  Without these overrides, the original compound assignments
`+=` and `-=` silently fail on GPU.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Remove guards around b/143684500.

Several kernels have previously been disabled for std::complex due
to lack of operator support on device.  This is no longer the case,
and these kernels can now be enabled.

NOTE: we also needed to replace `a+=b` and `a-=b` with `a=a+b` and
`a=a-b` for use with `std::complex<T>` on device.  Unfortunately MSVC
does not stricly follow the c++ standard, and unnecessarily specializes
these operators. This prevents us from using Eigen's device-compatible
overrides.  Without these overrides, the original compound assignments
`+=` and `-=` silently fail on GPU.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Remove guards around b/143684500.

Several kernels have previously been disabled for std::complex due
to lack of operator support on device.  This is no longer the case,
and these kernels can now be enabled.

NOTE: we also needed to replace `a+=b` and `a-=b` with `a=a+b` and
`a=a-b` for use with `std::complex<T>` on device.  Unfortunately MSVC
does not stricly follow the c++ standard, and unnecessarily specializes
these operators. This prevents us from using Eigen's device-compatible
overrides.  Without these overrides, the original compound assignments
`+=` and `-=` silently fail on GPU.

  vectorized types, but it is not actually needed: the use of 'const
  __restrict__' means the kernel still generates LDG instructions

The following commit breaks the ROCm CSB (errors while running GPU unit tests)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47398

```
ERROR: /root/tensorflow/tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/BUILD:573:13: undeclared inclusion(s) in rule '//tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests:hlo_to_llvm_ir':
this rule is missing dependency declarations for the following files included by 'tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/hlo_to_llvm_ir.cc':
  'tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/nvptx_compiler.h'
Target //tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests:constant.hlo.test failed to build
```

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

Change-Id: I14bb20f896edbd66011ecf3c42782da166d83c51","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/4b0772501a0a1b5c95930c38c7a32e3d3ebe6e7c"},{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

Signed-off-by: Waqar Hameed <whame91@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0"},{"sha":"1dae6b1f81ed42cc94f8706348506190d16880dc","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Lazy load optional modules to speedup pip package import","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/1dae6b1f81ed42cc94f8706348506190d16880dc"},{"sha":"dc294316e71debecf1daf6c3de2dc88d054df5d2","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix lazy kubernetes import","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/dc294316e71debecf1daf6c3de2dc88d054df5d2"},{"sha":"6129e865feed81b7f2284d11b41cac94a048ba29","author":{"name":"Yuriy Chernyshov","email":"790e5e6b6805314dc608d4277ae91d20c7b35e33@yandex-team.ru"},"message":"Mark header-implemented functions as inline

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PR #47767: lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47767

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`)...

Change-Id: Id8b45da0979addc953c147189ee3abf23594a1f0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/d58a39730d73f7076cdae020da6a4a8954f1d3f4"},{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

Change-Id: Id8b45da0979addc953c147189ee3abf23594a1f0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/d58a39730d73f7076cdae020da6a4a8954f1d3f4"},{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363888478
Change-Id: I14bb20f896edbd66011ecf3c42782da166d83c51","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/4b0772501a0a1b5c95930c38c7a32e3d3ebe6e7c"},{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

Signed-off-by: Waqar Hameed <whame91@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0"},{"sha":"1dae6b1f81ed42cc94f8706348506190d16880dc","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Lazy load optional modules to speedup pip package import","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/1dae6b1f81ed42cc94f8706348506190d16880dc"},{"sha":"dc294316e71debecf1daf6c3de2dc88d054df5d2","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix lazy kubernetes import","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/dc294316e71debecf1daf6c3de2dc88d054df5d2"},{"sha":"6129e865feed81b7f2284d11b41cac94a048ba29","author":{"name":"Yuriy Chernyshov","email":"790e5e6b6805314dc608d4277ae91d20c7b35e33@yandex-team.ru"},"message":"Mark header-implemented functions as inline

[{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47767

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`)...

Change-Id: Id8b45da0979addc953c147189ee3abf23594a1f0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/d58a39730d73f7076cdae020da6a4a8954f1d3f4"},{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

We added this unstable feature a few years ago, as a way to opt out of
context updates, but it didn't prove useful in practice.

We have other proposals for how to address the same problem, like
context selectors.

Since it was prefixed with `unstable_`, we should be able to remove it
without consequence. The hook API already warned if you used it.

Even if someone is using it somewhere, it's meant to be an optimization
only, so if they are using the API properly, it should not have any

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47767

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`)...

Change-Id: Id8b45da0979addc953c147189ee3abf23594a1f0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/d58a39730d73f7076cdae020da6a4a8954f1d3f4"},{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

- This commit chooses the optimal vector size that is compatible with
  the data shape and pointer alignment.
- Note that the ldg function would require more changes to support the
  vectorized types, but it is not actually needed: the use of 'const
  __restrict__' means the kernel still generates LDG instructions
  without it.
- Some quick benchmarking showed the following speedups with this commit
  when gathering vectors of length 256 on an NVIDIA TITAN V GPU:

Change-Id: Id8b45da0979addc953c147189ee3abf23594a1f0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Geolem/tensorflow/commits/d58a39730d73f7076cdae020da6a4a8954f1d3f4"},{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PR #47767: lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47767

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`)...

Change-Id: Id8b45da0979addc953c147189ee3abf23594a1f0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/d58a39730d73f7076cdae020da6a4a8954f1d3f4"},{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

[{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363888478
Change-Id: I14bb20f896edbd66011ecf3c42782da166d83c51","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/4b0772501a0a1b5c95930c38c7a32e3d3ebe6e7c"},{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363910046
Change-Id: I4baa292e5937d115d996c15926fca21ff085bb53","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/aa3bd9f6de5a76c4c226548a48e448d211978e92"},{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

Signed-off-by: Waqar Hameed <whame91@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0"},{"sha":"1dae6b1f81ed42cc94f8706348506190d16880dc","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Lazy load optional modules to speedup pip package import","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/1dae6b1f81ed42cc94f8706348506190d16880dc"},{"sha":"dc294316e71debecf1daf6c3de2dc88d054df5d2","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix lazy kubernetes import","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/dc294316e71debecf1daf6c3de2dc88d054df5d2"},{"sha":"6129e865feed81b7f2284d11b41cac94a048ba29","author":{"name":"Yuriy Chernyshov","email":"790e5e6b6805314dc608d4277ae91d20c7b35e33@yandex-team.ru"},"message":"Mark header-implemented functions as inline

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363910046
Change-Id: I4baa292e5937d115d996c15926fca21ff085bb53","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/aa3bd9f6de5a76c4c226548a48e448d211978e92"},{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363888478
Change-Id: I14bb20f896edbd66011ecf3c42782da166d83c51","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/4b0772501a0a1b5c95930c38c7a32e3d3ebe6e7c"},{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363910046
Change-Id: I4baa292e5937d115d996c15926fca21ff085bb53","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/aa3bd9f6de5a76c4c226548a48e448d211978e92"},{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the

[{"sha":"a629b8bcc1932cd3af234f6b9b15398c380df9bb","author":{"name":"Patrik Laurell","email":"a8cf9c79e9694fb928300c193c08271c49ca424d@arm.com"},"message":"Update CMSIS ref kernel wrappers.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/a629b8bcc1932cd3af234f6b9b15398c380df9bb"},{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PR #47767: lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47767

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`)...

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363948229
Change-Id: Id8b45da0979addc953c147189ee3abf23594a1f0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/d58a39730d73f7076cdae020da6a4a8954f1d3f4"},{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PR #47767: lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47767

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`)...

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363948229
Change-Id: Id8b45da0979addc953c147189ee3abf23594a1f0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/d58a39730d73f7076cdae020da6a4a8954f1d3f4"},{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and

!tf.resource subtypes.

already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PR #47767: lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47767

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`)...

[{"sha":"a629b8bcc1932cd3af234f6b9b15398c380df9bb","author":{"name":"Patrik Laurell","email":"a8cf9c79e9694fb928300c193c08271c49ca424d@arm.com"},"message":"Update CMSIS ref kernel wrappers.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/a629b8bcc1932cd3af234f6b9b15398c380df9bb"},{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

Change-Id: Id8b45da0979addc953c147189ee3abf23594a1f0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/d58a39730d73f7076cdae020da6a4a8954f1d3f4"},{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Geolem/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

Signed-off-by: Waqar Hameed <whame91@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Geolem/tensorflow/commits/9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0"},{"sha":"1dae6b1f81ed42cc94f8706348506190d16880dc","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Lazy load optional modules to speedup pip package import","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Geolem/tensorflow/commits/1dae6b1f81ed42cc94f8706348506190d16880dc"},{"sha":"dc294316e71debecf1daf6c3de2dc88d054df5d2","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix lazy kubernetes import","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Geolem/tensorflow/commits/dc294316e71debecf1daf6c3de2dc88d054df5d2"},{"sha":"6129e865feed81b7f2284d11b41cac94a048ba29","author":{"name":"Yuriy Chernyshov","email":"790e5e6b6805314dc608d4277ae91d20c7b35e33@yandex-team.ru"},"message":"Mark header-implemented functions as inline

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363888478
Change-Id: I14bb20f896edbd66011ecf3c42782da166d83c51","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Geolem/tensorflow/commits/4b0772501a0a1b5c95930c38c7a32e3d3ebe6e7c"},{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

Signed-off-by: Waqar Hameed Change-Id: I4baa292e5937d115d996c15926fca21ff085bb53","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Geolem/tensorflow/commits/aa3bd9f6de5a76c4c226548a48e448d211978e92"},{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

[{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363888478
Change-Id: I14bb20f896edbd66011ecf3c42782da166d83c51","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/4b0772501a0a1b5c95930c38c7a32e3d3ebe6e7c"},{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.
