Change-Id: I14bb20f896edbd66011ecf3c42782da166d83c51","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/4b0772501a0a1b5c95930c38c7a32e3d3ebe6e7c"},{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363888478
Change-Id: I14bb20f896edbd66011ecf3c42782da166d83c51","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/4b0772501a0a1b5c95930c38c7a32e3d3ebe6e7c"},{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

Signed-off-by: Waqar Hameed <whame91@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0"},{"sha":"1dae6b1f81ed42cc94f8706348506190d16880dc","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Lazy load optional modules to speedup pip package import","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/1dae6b1f81ed42cc94f8706348506190d16880dc"},{"sha":"dc294316e71debecf1daf6c3de2dc88d054df5d2","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix lazy kubernetes import","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/dc294316e71debecf1daf6c3de2dc88d054df5d2"},{"sha":"6129e865feed81b7f2284d11b41cac94a048ba29","author":{"name":"Yuriy Chernyshov","email":"790e5e6b6805314dc608d4277ae91d20c7b35e33@yandex-team.ru"},"message":"Mark header-implemented functions as inline

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedforgood/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

Signed-off-by: Waqar Hameed <whame91@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedforgood/tensorflow/commits/9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0"},{"sha":"1dae6b1f81ed42cc94f8706348506190d16880dc","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Lazy load optional modules to speedup pip package import","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedforgood/tensorflow/commits/1dae6b1f81ed42cc94f8706348506190d16880dc"},{"sha":"dc294316e71debecf1daf6c3de2dc88d054df5d2","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix lazy kubernetes import","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedforgood/tensorflow/commits/dc294316e71debecf1daf6c3de2dc88d054df5d2"},{"sha":"6129e865feed81b7f2284d11b41cac94a048ba29","author":{"name":"Yuriy Chernyshov","email":"790e5e6b6805314dc608d4277ae91d20c7b35e33@yandex-team.ru"},"message":"Mark header-implemented functions as inline

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363888478
Change-Id: I14bb20f896edbd66011ecf3c42782da166d83c51","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedforgood/tensorflow/commits/4b0772501a0a1b5c95930c38c7a32e3d3ebe6e7c"},{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363910046
Change-Id: I4baa292e5937d115d996c15926fca21ff085bb53","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/aa3bd9f6de5a76c4c226548a48e448d211978e92"},{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47767

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.

negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,

will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`)...

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363910046
Change-Id: I4baa292e5937d115d996c15926fca21ff085bb53","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/aa3bd9f6de5a76c4c226548a48e448d211978e92"},{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363910046
Change-Id: I4baa292e5937d115d996c15926fca21ff085bb53","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/aa3bd9f6de5a76c4c226548a48e448d211978e92"},{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PR #47767: lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47767

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`)...

This was already the case in TF1, but in TF2, InputSpec.dtype previously was checked both before and after the inputs were casted, requiring the input dtype before the cast and the compute dtype to match InputSpec.dtype. Now it's only checked before inputs are casted

[{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

Change-Id: I4baa292e5937d115d996c15926fca21ff085bb53","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/aa3bd9f6de5a76c4c226548a48e448d211978e92"},{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PR #47767: lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47767

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`)...

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47767

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`)...

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363910046
Change-Id: I4baa292e5937d115d996c15926fca21ff085bb53","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedforgood/tensorflow/commits/aa3bd9f6de5a76c4c226548a48e448d211978e92"},{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47767

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`)...

[{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

* Fix ESLint crash on empty react effect hook

* Add layout effect to test

* Improve wording in comment

* Improve lint warning wording

* Reword missing effect callback message","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/LesterWeng/react/commits/e8eff119e036485b74b2acb6f57045390703f6fb"},{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/LesterWeng/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/LesterWeng/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/LesterWeng/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"},{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/LesterWeng/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"},{"sha":"fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Retry with fresh otp if publish fails (#20582)

Currently, if publishing a package fails, the script crashes, and the
user must start it again from the beginning. Usually this happens
because the one-time password has timed out.

With this change, the user will be prompted for a fresh otp, and the
script will resume publishing.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/LesterWeng/react/commits/fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf"},{"sha":"a656ace8da6d005e49a750da3d9a3fd0fdcac76c","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Deletion effects should fire parent -> child (#20584)

We need to call `detachFiberAfterEffects` on the fiber's alternate to
clean it up. We're currently not, because the `alternate` field is
cleared during `detachFiberMutation`. So I deferred detaching the
`alternate` until the passive phase. Only the `return` pointer needs to

DevTools was built with a fork of an early idea for how Suspense cache might work. This idea is incompatible with newer APIs like `useTransition` which unfortunately prevented me from making certain UX improvements. This PR swaps out the primary usage of this cache (there are a few) in favor of the newer `unstable_getCacheForType` and `unstable_useCacheRefresh` APIs. We can go back and update the others in follow up PRs.

### Messaging changes

I've refactored the way the frontend loads component props/state/etc to hopefully make it better match the Suspense+cache model. Doing this gave up some of the small optimizations I'd added but hopefully the actual performance impact of that is minor and the overall ergonomic improvements of working with the cache API make this worth it.

The backend no longer remembers inspected paths. Instead, the frontend sends them every time and the backend sends a response with those paths. I've also added a new "force" parameter that the frontend can use to tell the backend to send a response even if the component hasn't rendered since the last time it asked. (This is used to get data for newly inspected paths.)

_Initial inspection..._
```
front |                                                      | back
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:[], force:true) ---------> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (full-data) -- |
```
_1 second passes with no updates..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:[], force:false) --------> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (no-change) -- |
```
_User clicks to expand a path, aka hydrate..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:['foo'], force:true) ----> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (full-data) -- |
```
_1 second passes during which there is an update..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:['foo'], force:false) ---> |
      | <----------------- "inspectedElement" (full-data) -- |
```

### Clear errors/warnings transition
Previously this meant there would be a delay after clicking the "clear" button. The UX after this change is much improved.

### Hydrating paths transition
I also added a transition to hydration (expanding "dehyrated" paths).

### Better error boundaries
I also added a lower-level error boundary in case the new suspense operation ever failed. It provides a better "retry" mechanism (select a new element) so DevTools doesn't become entirely useful. Here I'm intentionally causing an error every time I select an element.

### Improved snapshot tests
I also migrated several of the existing snapshot tests to use inline snapshots and added a new serializer for dehydrated props. Inline snapshots are easier to verify and maintain and the new serializer means dehydrated props will be formatted in a way that makes sense rather than being empty (in external snapshots) or super verbose (default inline snapshot format).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/LesterWeng/react/commits/af16f755dc7e0d6e2b4bf79b86c434f4ce0497fe"},{"sha":"ba9582da27481677cdac2dd000a438147a5df88e","author":{"name":"ChenLei","email":"2078e632128f17c4aa4e413d134a36c7418bccff@qq.com"},"message":"[devtools] Fix can't expand prop value in some scenario (#20534)

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

Change-Id: I14bb20f896edbd66011ecf3c42782da166d83c51","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/4b0772501a0a1b5c95930c38c7a32e3d3ebe6e7c"},{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

Change-Id: I4baa292e5937d115d996c15926fca21ff085bb53","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/aa3bd9f6de5a76c4c226548a48e448d211978e92"},{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

Signed-off-by: Waqar Hameed <whame91@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0"},{"sha":"1dae6b1f81ed42cc94f8706348506190d16880dc","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Lazy load optional modules to speedup pip package import","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/1dae6b1f81ed42cc94f8706348506190d16880dc"},{"sha":"a629b8bcc1932cd3af234f6b9b15398c380df9bb","author":{"name":"Patrik Laurell","email":"a8cf9c79e9694fb928300c193c08271c49ca424d@arm.com"},"message":"Update CMSIS ref kernel wrappers.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/a629b8bcc1932cd3af234f6b9b15398c380df9bb"},{"sha":"dc294316e71debecf1daf6c3de2dc88d054df5d2","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix lazy kubernetes import","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/dc294316e71debecf1daf6c3de2dc88d054df5d2"},{"sha":"6129e865feed81b7f2284d11b41cac94a048ba29","author":{"name":"Yuriy Chernyshov","email":"790e5e6b6805314dc608d4277ae91d20c7b35e33@yandex-team.ru"},"message":"Mark header-implemented functions as inline

This makes their signature to match functions from above.
It also solves duplicate symbol errors in certain conditions.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/6129e865feed81b7f2284d11b41cac94a048ba29"},{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363910046
Change-Id: I4baa292e5937d115d996c15926fca21ff085bb53","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/aa3bd9f6de5a76c4c226548a48e448d211978e92"},{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PR #47767: lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47767

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`)...

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

Signed-off-by: Waqar Hameed <whame91@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0"},{"sha":"1dae6b1f81ed42cc94f8706348506190d16880dc","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Lazy load optional modules to speedup pip package import","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/1dae6b1f81ed42cc94f8706348506190d16880dc"},{"sha":"a629b8bcc1932cd3af234f6b9b15398c380df9bb","author":{"name":"Patrik Laurell","email":"a8cf9c79e9694fb928300c193c08271c49ca424d@arm.com"},"message":"Update CMSIS ref kernel wrappers.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/a629b8bcc1932cd3af234f6b9b15398c380df9bb"},{"sha":"dc294316e71debecf1daf6c3de2dc88d054df5d2","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix lazy kubernetes import","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/dc294316e71debecf1daf6c3de2dc88d054df5d2"},{"sha":"6129e865feed81b7f2284d11b41cac94a048ba29","author":{"name":"Yuriy Chernyshov","email":"790e5e6b6805314dc608d4277ae91d20c7b35e33@yandex-team.ru"},"message":"Mark header-implemented functions as inline

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363910046
Change-Id: I4baa292e5937d115d996c15926fca21ff085bb53","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/aa3bd9f6de5a76c4c226548a48e448d211978e92"},{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363910046
Change-Id: I4baa292e5937d115d996c15926fca21ff085bb53","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/aa3bd9f6de5a76c4c226548a48e448d211978e92"},{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

This makes their signature to match functions from above.
It also solves duplicate symbol errors in certain conditions.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/6129e865feed81b7f2284d11b41cac94a048ba29"},{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363888478
Change-Id: I14bb20f896edbd66011ecf3c42782da166d83c51","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/4b0772501a0a1b5c95930c38c7a32e3d3ebe6e7c"},{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

[{"sha":"bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Re-enabling unit-tests that are now passing on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/bc5c5223e9e80f37dc7590f0203ab6726f714338"},{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363888478
Change-Id: I14bb20f896edbd66011ecf3c42782da166d83c51","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/4b0772501a0a1b5c95930c38c7a32e3d3ebe6e7c"},{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363888478
Change-Id: I14bb20f896edbd66011ecf3c42782da166d83c51","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/4b0772501a0a1b5c95930c38c7a32e3d3ebe6e7c"},{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

[{"sha":"bcc08de62e427a7c10b64204bb2b1de252f2dd05","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PR #47767: lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47767

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`)...

The "userxattr" option is needed for mounting overlayfs inside a user namespace with kernel >= 5.11.

The "userxattr" option is NOT needed for the initial user namespace (aka "the host").

Also, Ubuntu (since circa 2015) and Debian (since 10) with kernel < 5.11 can mount the overlayfs in a user namespace without the "userxattr" option.

The corresponding kernel commit: 2d2f2d7322ff43e0fe92bf8cccdc0b09449bf2e1
> **ovl: user xattr**
>
> Optionally allow using "user.overlay." namespace instead of "trusted.overlay."
> ...
> Disable redirect_dir and metacopy options, because these would allow privilege escalation through direct manipulation of the
> "user.overlay.redirect" or "user.overlay.metacopy" xattrs.

Fix issue 42055

Related to containerd/containerd PR 5076

the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Remove cli test for duplicate --net/--network opts","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bearstech/moby/commits/e0c87f90cd93fbbfe1ba0e0abc80ba757e3b0a82"},{"sha":"5a664dc87d79ddc9f09c7a963c52f491999dc939","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"jsonfile: more defensive reader implementation

Tonis mentioned that we can run into issues if there is more error
handling added here. This adds a custom reader implementation which is
like io.MultiReader except it does not cache EOF's.
What got us into trouble in the first place is `io.MultiReader` will
always return EOF once it has received an EOF, however the error
handling that we are going for is to recover from an EOF because the
underlying file is a file which can have more data added to it after
EOF.
